    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
      <p>Collection contains correspondence concerning Mrs. Richardson's literary career, clippings, scrapbooks, and
         manuscripts of many speeches, scripts, articles, short stories and novels including 
         <title xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" render="italic" xlink:href="">Little Aleck</title>, 
         <title xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" render="italic" xlink:href="">The Influence of Men-Incurable</title>,
         <title xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" render="italic" xlink:href="">Lonesome Journey</title>, and 
         <title xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" render="italic" xlink:href="">The Woman Speaker</title>.</p>
      <p>Her histories of the quartermaster corps are included. Very
         little material from her suffrage career is present.</p>
      <p>There is correspondence with many prominent contemporary
         Virginia political and literary figures including John
         Erskine, Ellen Glasgow, Harry Flood Byrd, and John Garland
         Pollard.</p>
    </scopecontent>
